insert into "books" ("average_rating", "buy_link", "description", "large_image_url", "list_price", "page_count", "published_at", "ratings_count", "thumbnail_image_url", "title") values (DEFAULT, DEFAULT, 'The crystal engineering of inorganic-organic hybrid materials, nominally metal organic frameworks and coordination polymers, has become an increasingly popular field of research over the past few decades owing to the potential for the synthesis of technologically important compounds with tailored topologies. These materials consist of metal centers tethered through multifunctional organic linkers to promote higher dimensional compounds. As such, self-assembly under hydrothermal conditions has been employed to synthesize extended dimensional homometallic and heterometallic actinide based coordination polymers. The uranium (VI) and thorium (IV) metal centers in these materials showed an affinity towards binding with the ligand in a bidentate fashion through a carboxylate oxygen atom and nitrogen from a heterocyclic aromatic forming a 5-membered ring. Additionally, the photophysical properties of the uranium based coordination polymers were investigated. The fluorescence of hexavalent uranium in both solution and the solid state is known to derive from vibronic transitions of the central uranyl moiety, UO22+. Upon excitation of the uranyl cation, the characteristic emission between 450-600 nm results from the symmetric stretching of the O=U bond with known vibronic frequency of 860 cm-1. The frequencies for the homometallic materials were calculated to range from 862-894 cm-1 agreeing with the literature value of 860 cm-1. The pyridinedicarboxylic acid series illustrated a fascinating feature in the emission spectra: shoulder peaks. Attempts to correlate the shoulder peaks with the geometric nature of the uranyl cation in each compound are presented herein. When the uranyl cation was excited in the heterometallic compounds within the 3,5-pyrazoledicarboxylic and 4,5-imidazoledicarboxylic acid systems, the characteristic emission was not detected. This observation indicates that the copper (II) metal centers may provide an alternative pathway for non-radiative decay. In compound 13, the copper and uranium metal centers are bridged through a uranyl oxygen atom. This change in the uranyl environment may also contribute to the lack of detectable uranyl emission. Conversely, uranyl emission was observed when either copper (II) or lead (II) was incorporated into the uranium-2,6-pyridinedicarboxylic acid system (compounds 8 and 11). This occurrence may be the first instance where uranyl emission was observed in the presence of a transition metal in the solid state. These photophysical properties along with the structural schematics of the various systems will be discussed.', DEFAULT, DEFAULT, '173', '2008', DEFAULT, 'http://books.google.com/books/content?id=EGKeGhZfzHIC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api', 'Controlling the Hydrothermal Conditions to Synthesize Novel Uranium-based Heterometallic Coordination Polymers and Their Subsequent Fluorescence Investigations')ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
